// Image List for Chapter 8: Analyzing Cells, Molecules, and Systems

- *Figure 8–1:* Microscopic life as seen by van Leeuwenhoek. (A) Bacteria from between his teeth. (B) The eukaryotic green alga Volvox. These early observations founded cell biology as a discipline.
- *Figure 8–2:* Light micrographs of cells in culture, including (A) mouse fibroblasts, (B) chick myoblasts fusing to form muscle cells, (C) purified rat retinal ganglion nerve cells, and (D) tobacco cells in liquid culture—illustrating the diversity of cultured cell morphologies.
- *Figure 8–3:* The production of hybrid cells by cell fusion. Shows how two cell types are mixed with a fusing agent to form heterokaryons, which then give rise to hybrid cells. If one parent is a tumor cell line, the hybrid is called a hybridoma, used to produce monoclonal antibodies.
- *Table 8–1:* Some commonly used eukaryotic cell lines, including NIH-3T3 (mouse fibroblast), HeLa (human cervical epithelial), CHO (Chinese hamster ovary), and others—showing cell type, origin, and major uses in research.
- *Figure 8–4:* The preparative ultracentrifuge. (A) Fixed-angle rotor design. (B) Swinging-bucket rotor design. Shows how samples are separated at high speed under a vacuum and refrigeration, with material sedimenting toward the bottom (or sides) of tubes.
- *Figure 8–5:* Cell fractionation by differential centrifugation. Illustrates how a cell homogenate is subjected to progressively higher centrifugal forces to pellet whole cells/nuclei, then mitochondria/lysosomes, then microsomes/vesicles, and finally ribosomes/large macromolecules.
- *Figure 8–6:* Comparison of velocity sedimentation (A) and equilibrium sedimentation (B). In velocity sedimentation, components separate by size and shape through a sucrose gradient. In equilibrium sedimentation, components migrate to their buoyant density position.
- *Figure 8–7:* Formation of subcellular structures in a cytoplasmic extract from Xenopus laevis eggs. (A) Nuclear envelope forms around sperm chromosomes in an interphase extract. (B) A mitotic spindle forms in a metaphase extract—demonstrating that cell-cycle-specific assembly can be recapitulated in vitro.
- *Figure 8–8:* The separation of molecules by column chromatography. A sample is applied to the top of a column filled with a gel matrix; different components travel at different rates and are collected separately as they emerge from the bottom.
- *Figure 8–9:* Three types of chromatography matrices. (A) Ion-exchange chromatography—separates by charge. (B) Gel-filtration chromatography—separates by size (small molecules enter pores and are retarded). (C) Affinity chromatography—retains proteins that specifically bind an immobilized ligand or antibody.
- *Figure 8–10:* Protein purification by successive chromatography steps. Graphs showing how the protein of interest (detected by enzymatic activity) is progressively enriched through ion-exchange (A), gel-filtration (B), and affinity (C) column steps.
- *Figure 8–11:* Epitope tagging for protein purification. A DNA sequence encoding a short peptide tag (epitope) is inserted into the gene of interest; the expressed tag allows rapid purification of the protein and any associated binding partners by immunoprecipitation or affinity chromatography.
- *Figure 8–12:* The detergent sodium dodecyl sulfate (SDS) and the reducing agent β-mercaptoethanol, the two reagents used to solubilize and denature proteins prior to SDS-PAGE. SDS unfolds proteins and imparts uniform negative charge; β-mercaptoethanol breaks disulfide bonds.
- *Figure 8–13:* SDS polyacrylamide-gel electrophoresis (SDS-PAGE). (A) Electrophoresis apparatus. (B) Diagram showing how SDS-coated polypeptides migrate through the polyacrylamide gel by size, with smaller proteins moving faster toward the positive electrode.
- *Figure 8–14:* Photograph of a Coomassie blue–stained SDS-PAGE gel showing progressive purification of a protein through successive chromatographic steps—each lane representing a step from crude extract to homogeneous enzyme.
- *Figure 8–15:* Separation of protein molecules by isoelectric focusing. A stable pH gradient is established in a tube gel; proteins migrate until they reach the position where the pH equals their isoelectric point and they have no net charge, forming sharp bands.
- *Figure 8–16:* Two-dimensional polyacrylamide-gel electrophoresis of all proteins in an E. coli cell. Each spot represents a distinct polypeptide separated first by isoelectric point (horizontal) and then by molecular mass (vertical), demonstrating resolution of the entire bacterial proteome.
- *Figure 8–17:* Western blotting. (A) Coomassie blue–stained gel of yeast proteins. (B) Western blot using antibodies against a specific protein, demonstrating how a single rare protein can be detected in a complex mixture after transfer to a membrane and antibody probing.
- *Figure 8–18:* The mass spectrometer. (A) Standard mass spectrometry (MS): ion source, mass analyzer, and detector are shown with a typical mass spectrum. (B) Tandem mass spectrometry (MS/MS): a first mass filter selects a precursor ion; collision fragments it; a second analyzer identifies fragment masses to determine the peptide sequence.
- *Figure 8–19:* Measurement of protein binding using fluorescence anisotropy. (A) A small fluorescent molecule tumbles freely (low anisotropy) but tumbles slowly when bound to a large receptor (high anisotropy). (B) A binding curve showing how anisotropy increases with receptor concentration, with 50% binding occurring at the Kd.
- *Figure 8–20:* X-ray crystallography. Shows a protein crystal (B, Rubisco), its x-ray diffraction pattern (C), and the resulting atomic model (D, E)—illustrating the complete workflow from crystal to 3D protein structure at near-atomic resolution.
- *Figure 8–21:* NMR spectroscopy. (A) A two-dimensional NMR spectrum showing chemical shifts of hydrogen nuclei in the cellulase C-terminal domain. (B) Ten superimposed computed structures consistent with the distance constraints, illustrating the high-resolution structural information obtainable in solution.
- *Figure 8–22:* Results of a BLAST sequence similarity search. The human cell-cycle regulatory protein Cdk1 is aligned with maize Cdk1 (68% identity), demonstrating how database searching can rapidly infer function for a newly discovered protein.
- *Figure 8–23:* Restriction nucleases cleave DNA at specific nucleotide sequences. Shows HaeIII (blunt-cut 4-bp palindrome), EcoRI, and HindIII (both producing 4-base 5′ overhangs, or "sticky ends") that facilitate downstream cloning.
- *Figure 8–24:* DNA gel electrophoresis. (A) Schematic of restriction digest separated on agarose. (B) Ethidium bromide–stained agarose gel. (C) Polyacrylamide gel resolving single-nucleotide differences in short DNA fragments. (D) Pulsed-field gel separating all 16 yeast chromosomes.
- *Figure 8–25:* Methods for labeling DNA molecules in vitro. (A) Incorporation of 32P-labeled nucleotides by DNA polymerase. (B) Incorporation of digoxigenin-labeled nucleotides to produce nonradioactive probes detected by antibody–fluorophore conjugates.
- *Figure 8–26:* Insertion of a DNA fragment into a bacterial plasmid using restriction nuclease and DNA ligase. The cut plasmid and insert (both made with the same enzyme) are mixed and ligated to form a recombinant plasmid. Electron micrographs confirm the inserted fragment.
- *Figure 8–27:* DNA ligase joining DNA fragments in vitro. (A) Joining two fragments cut by the same restriction nuclease (EcoRI) with complementary sticky ends. (B) Joining fragments cut by different enzymes after blunt-ending with DNA polymerase, showing the versatility of ligation.
- *Figure 8–28:* Amplification of a cloned DNA fragment inside a bacterial cell. The recombinant plasmid is introduced into bacteria; as the cells multiply, billions of identical copies of the plasmid (and the inserted gene) are produced and can subsequently be harvested and purified.
- *Figure 8–29:* Construction of a human genomic DNA library. Chromosomal DNA is cut with a restriction nuclease, fragments are inserted into plasmids, and the collection of recombinant plasmids—each carrying a different fragment—is introduced into E. coli to represent the entire genome.
- *Figure 8–30:* Synthesis of complementary DNA (cDNA) from mRNA. Reverse transcriptase copies the mRNA into a single-strand cDNA; RNase H and DNA polymerase complete synthesis of double-strand cDNA, which is then cloned to form a cDNA library enriched for protein-coding sequences.
- *Figure 8–31:* DNA denaturation and renaturation (hybridization). Heating separates the two strands of a DNA double helix; slow cooling allows complementary strands to re-form hydrogen bonds and reconstitute the double helix. This principle underpins all nucleic acid hybridization techniques.
- *Figure 8–32:* In situ hybridization (FISH) to locate genes on isolated chromosomes. Six fluorescent DNA probes mark their complementary sequences on both copies of human chromosome 5, showing that each probe produces two dots per chromosome due to prior DNA replication.
- *Figure 8–33:* A pair of PCR primers directs the selective synthesis of a desired DNA segment. In each cycle, strands are separated by heat, primers anneal, and DNA polymerase extends them—specifically amplifying only the sequence bracketed by the two primers.
- *Figure 8–34:* PCR amplification through repeated cycles. After 20–30 cycles, the target sequence (bounded by the two primers) is exponentially amplified, with all newly synthesized strands serving as templates in subsequent rounds, generating billions of copies.
- *Figure 8–35:* PCR can produce either genomic clones (A) from total DNA with appropriate flanking primers, or cDNA clones (B) by first performing reverse transcription of the target mRNA and then amplifying the resulting cDNA with a second primer.
- *Figure 8–36:* PCR detection of a viral genome (SARS-CoV-2) in a nasal sample. Even a few copies of viral RNA are reverse-transcribed and amplified to a detectable level, illustrating the extreme sensitivity of PCR-based diagnostics.
- *Figure 8–37:* PCR in forensic science using short tandem repeats (STRs). (A) Analysis of one STR locus produces two bands (maternal and paternal alleles). (B) Comparison of three STR loci from three suspects and a forensic sample reveals a unique DNA fingerprint that matches suspect B.
- *Figure 8–38:* DNA cloning by Gibson assembly. A restriction-linearized plasmid and a PCR product (with overlapping sequences at both ends) are treated with 5′ exonuclease to create single-strand overhangs; complementary ends anneal, DNA polymerase fills gaps, and ligase seals nicks.
- *Figure 8–39:* Production of large amounts of a protein using an expression vector. A protein-coding sequence is inserted downstream of a strong promoter in a plasmid; introduction into bacterial, yeast, insect, or mammalian cells drives high-level mRNA and protein synthesis.
- *Figure 8–40:* Overexpression of a DNA helicase using a plasmid expression vector in bacteria. SDS-PAGE shows that at the permissive temperature (25°C) no helicase is detected, but after shifting to 42°C the helicase becomes the most abundant protein in the lysate.
- *Figure 8–41:* Recombinant DNA techniques enable bidirectional movement between gene and protein. Starting from a protein (identified by mass spectrometry), one can search databases to find the gene, clone it, overexpress and purify the protein, then study both structure and function.
- *Figure 8–42:* The dideoxy (chain-terminating) nucleotide used in Sanger sequencing. Dideoxyribonucleoside triphosphates (ddNTPs) lack the 3′-OH group present in normal dNTPs, so once incorporated they prevent further chain elongation and terminate synthesis at specific positions.
- *Figure 8–43:* Automated dideoxy (Sanger) sequencing using four differently colored fluorescent ddNTPs. The resulting ladder of fragments is resolved by capillary electrophoresis; a camera records the sequence of colored bands, which a computer converts to a nucleotide sequence.
- *Figure 8–44:* Illumina second-generation sequencing. (A) Clusters of ~1000 identical DNA copies are generated on a glass flow cell. (B) Sequencing-by-synthesis uses reversible, fluorescent chain-terminating nucleotides added one at a time; each cycle is imaged, then the dye/blocker is removed, allowing the next nucleotide to be added—enabling massively parallel sequencing.
- *Figure 8–45:* Single-molecule real-time (SMRT) sequencing. A single DNA polymerase anchored in a nanoscale well copies a long template; each incorporated nucleotide carries a fluorescent dye on the terminal phosphate that emits a brief pulse of light before being released—enabling very long reads.
- *Figure 8–46:* Finding protein-coding regions in a DNA sequence. (A) Any linear DNA sequence contains six possible reading frames (three per strand). (B) Open reading frames (ORFs) are identified by the absence of stop codons over a long stretch, and they are compared with protein databases (e.g., using BLAST) to annotate gene function.
- *Figure 8–47:* Insertional mutant of the snapdragon Antirrhinum, where a mutation in a single gene causes leafy shoots to develop in place of flowers—an example of how insertional mutagenesis can reveal a gene's role in development.
- *Figure 8–48:* Screening for temperature-sensitive bacterial or yeast mutants by replica plating. Colonies are grown at a permissive temperature (23°C) and replicated to two plates, one kept at the permissive and one shifted to the restrictive temperature (36°C). Temperature-sensitive mutants fail to grow only at the restrictive condition.
- *Figure 8–49:* Types of gene mutations affecting their protein product. Shows loss-of-function mutations (point mutation, truncation, deletion), a conditional (temperature-sensitive) loss-of-function mutation, and a gain-of-function mutation that increases protein activity.
- *Figure 8–50:* A complementation test reveals that two strains of white birds carry recessive mutations in different genes. When crossed, the offspring have normal coloration—demonstrating that each parent contributes a functional copy of the gene the other parent lacks.
- *Figure 8–51:* Using genetics to determine gene order in the secretory pathway. Secretory mutant A accumulates protein in the ER; secretory mutant B accumulates protein in the Golgi. The double mutant AB accumulates protein in the ER, proving that the gene defective in A acts before the gene defective in B.
- *Figure 8–52:* Single-nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs) are positions in the genome where the nucleotide sequence differs between individuals in the population. Blocks of SNPs (haplotypes) are inherited together, enabling GWAS studies that link specific SNP patterns to disease susceptibility.
- *Figure 8–53:* Genes that affect a common disease, identified by genome-wide association studies (GWAS). Many SNPs spread throughout the genome are associated with modest increases in disease risk; in aggregate, they can account for a substantial portion of disease heritability.
- *Figure 8–54:* Engineered genes that can be turned on and off with small molecules. A chimeric transcription factor (DNA-binding domain fused to a ligand-binding domain) activates or represses a target gene only in the presence of a specific small-molecule ligand—enabling conditional, inducible gene expression.
- *Figure 8–55:* Summary of procedures for making gene replacements in mice. ES cells are transfected with an altered gene; cells with correct homologous recombination are identified and injected into early embryos; chimeric mice are bred to produce heterozygous and then homozygous knockout mice.
- *Figure 8–56:* Transgenic mice expressing a mutant DNA helicase (Xpd) show premature aging. Compared to a wild-type mouse (A), the transgenic mouse (B) exhibits osteoporosis, emaciation, early graying, and infertility—demonstrating that accumulated DNA damage drives aging.
- *Figure 8–57:* Use of CRISPR–Cas9 to study gene function. (A, B) Cas9 directed by a guide RNA cleaves a target gene; homologous recombination introduces a precise mutation. (C, D) Catalytically inactive Cas9 fused to a transcription activator or repressor can turn genes on or off without cutting.
- *Figure 8–58:* Making bar-coded collections of mutant organisms. Each yeast deletion construct contains sequences homologous to the target gene, a selectable marker, and a unique ~20 bp DNA "bar code," allowing rapid identification of each mutant strain by sequencing.
- *Figure 8–59:* Genome-wide fitness screens using a pooled library of bar-coded yeast deletion mutants. After growth under a test condition, the relative abundance of each mutant's bar code is measured by DNA sequencing, revealing which genes are essential, beneficial, or dispensable under that condition.
- *Figure 8–60:* RNA interference (RNAi) to test gene function in C. elegans. (A) Worms are fed E. coli expressing a dsRNA matching the target gene. (B, C) Wild-type embryos show normal pronuclear migration; embryos with a specific gene knocked down by RNAi fail to migrate, revealing the gene's role in embryonic development.
- *Figure 8–61:* Genome-wide RNAi screen in C. elegans using a 96-well plate. Each well contains E. coli expressing a different dsRNA, one per gene. After several days, worms are examined microscopically; wells with sterile worms (compared to wild-type) identify genes required for fertility.
- *Figure 8–62:* Using reporter genes to determine a gene's expression pattern. The coding sequence of gene X is replaced by a reporter gene (e.g., GFP or β-galactosidase) under control of candidate cis-regulatory sequences, revealing which sequences drive expression in specific cell types or conditions.
- *Figure 8–63:* In situ hybridization reveals gene expression patterns in a Drosophila embryo. Fluorescent probes for eve (magenta) and ftz (green) mRNAs show the characteristic stripe pattern of these segmentation genes, demonstrating the spatial precision of gene expression during development.
- *Figure 8–64:* RNA levels measured by quantitative RT-PCR (qRT-PCR). Fluorescence generated by a dye that binds double-strand PCR products accumulates more rapidly in the sample with higher initial mRNA concentration, enabling precise quantification of transcript levels.
- *Figure 8–65:* Cluster analysis to identify coordinately regulated genes. Expression data from human fibroblasts responding to serum show that wound-healing genes are upregulated (red), while cell-cycle and cholesterol biosynthesis genes are downregulated (green)—linking co-expressed genes to common biological processes.
- *Figure 8–66:* Single-cell RNA-seq identifies cell types in the planarian flatworm. (A) The flatworm model organism. (B) ~67,000 single cells are clustered by similar expression profiles and displayed as a two-dimensional scatter plot, revealing ~44 distinct cell types with distinct gene expression signatures.
- *Figure 8–67:* Chromatin immunoprecipitation (ChIP). Proteins are cross-linked to DNA in living cells; the DNA is sheared; an antibody against a transcription regulator precipitates associated DNA fragments; these are amplified by PCR and sequenced to map all genomic binding sites of the regulator.
- *Figure 8–68:* ChIP-seq results showing proteins bound near the Oct4 gene in embryonic stem cells. Binding profiles of Oct4, Sox2, and Nanog (key pluripotency regulators) are shown along with histone modification marks and RNA-seq data, revealing the cis-regulatory architecture of Oct4.
- *Figure 8–69:* Ribosome profiling. Total RNA from cells is digested with ribonuclease; only RNA sequences protected by ribosomes survive. These fragments are sequenced and mapped to the genome, providing a quantitative snapshot of exactly which mRNAs are being actively translated.
- *Figure 8–70:* Ribosome profiling reveals a previously unannotated gene encoding a protein of only 20 amino acids. Among two known viral genes, the profiling data shows a new, highly expressed open reading frame between them that was not recognized by conventional annotation.
- *Figure 8–71:* Production of transgenic plants using Agrobacterium. A leaf disc is incubated with bacteria carrying a recombinant plasmid; bacteria inject DNA into plant cells; only cells that take up and express the selectable marker survive and proliferate into a callus, which is then induced to regenerate a whole transgenic plant.
- *Figure 8–72:* "Golden rice" produced by recombinant DNA technology. (A) Pathway showing two heterologous enzyme-coding genes (from maize and a bacterium) added to rice endosperm to allow β-carotene synthesis. (B) Wild-type white rice grains. (C) Golden rice grains with high β-carotene content, showing the deep yellow/orange color.
- *Figure 8–73:* Diagrams summarizing biochemical relationships. A bar-headed arrow represents transcriptional repression; a standard arrow represents transcriptional activation. These cartoons are the starting point for quantitative mathematical modeling of gene regulatory networks.
- *Figure 8–74:* A simple transcriptional activation interaction. (A) Gene A produces an activator that binds promoter pX to drive expression of gene X. (B–E) Mathematical derivation of equilibrium binding equations showing how the fraction of pX occupied (and hence gene X activity) depends on activator concentration [A] and equilibrium constant K.
- *Figure 8–75:* Using an ordinary differential equation to study binding dynamics. (A) Equation 8–4 for the rate of change of bound promoter complex [A:pX]. (B) Solutions showing that after a 10-fold increase in [A], bound complex takes 5–40 seconds to reach its new steady state, depending on the kinetic rate constants.
- *Figure 8–76:* Effect of protein lifetime on the timing of gene expression response. (A) Rate equations for transcription, protein production, and degradation. (B, C) Differential equation and steady-state expression for protein X. (D, E) The time to reach a new steady state is directly proportional to protein lifetime τ.
- *Figure 8–77:* Promoter occupancy as a function of transcription regulator concentration. (A) Equations for bound and unbound fractions for a repressor. (B) For an activator A, gene activity is proportional to the bound fraction; half-maximal activity at [A] = 1/K. (C) For a repressor R, gene activity is proportional to the unbound fraction.
- *Figure 8–78:* A simple negative feedback motif. (A) Gene A activates gene R; protein R represses gene A. (B) Coupled differential equations (Equation set 8–8) for [A] and [R]. (C) The system with negative feedback (blue) reaches steady state faster than a system with no feedback (red).
- *Figure 8–79:* The stabilizing effect of negative feedback. When the transcription rate constant βA fluctuates by 25%, the system with negative feedback (left) shows smaller deviations in steady-state [R] than the system without feedback (right), demonstrating robustness to perturbations.
- *Figure 8–80:* Oscillations arising from delayed negative feedback. A three-component feedback loop converges quickly to steady state (A, B), whereas a five-component loop with the same rate constants exhibits stable sustained oscillations (C, D)—showing that loop length can switch a system from damped to oscillatory behavior.
- *Figure 8–81:* Cooperative binding of transcription regulators. (A) Hill coefficient h is added to the binding equation to model cooperativity. (B) As h increases, the bound fraction (for an activator, left) or unbound fraction (for a repressor, right) shows a progressively steeper, more switch-like dependence on regulator concentration.
- *Figure 8–82:* Positive feedback of a gene onto itself through serially connected activators and repressors. (A) Direct autoactivation. (B) Activation through an intermediate. (C) Activation through two intermediate repressors (double negative). All three circuits generate a net positive feedback loop.
- *Figure 8–83:* Nullcline analysis of a bistable positive feedback system. (A) X represses Y and Y represses X. (B) Coupled differential equations. (C) Steady-state equations for [X] and [Y]. (D) Three possible steady states (two stable, one unstable) arise when cooperativity is high. (E) Only one steady state when cooperativity is low.
- *Figure 8–84:* Stability analysis of steady states. (A) Dynamic trajectories (green) for various initial conditions converge on only two of the three possible steady states; the middle state is unstable. (B) Small perturbations return the system to its current steady state; large perturbations can flip the switch to the alternate state.
- *Figure 8–85:* Combinatorial control of gene expression using logic gates. (A) AND NOT gate: an activator A and repressor R control a gene; transcription occurs only when A is bound and R is not. (B) AND gate: two activators A1 and A2 must both be present to drive transcription.
- *Figure 8–86:* Quantitative output of combinatorial gene control. (A) Probability formula for the AND NOT logic gate (A and not R). (B, C) Heatmaps of gene expression depending on relative binding affinities KA and KR. (D) Heatmap for AND logic (two activators). (E) Experimental arabinose/cAMP data from E. coli closely matches the AND logic model.
- *Figure 8–87:* An incoherent feed-forward motif generates a pulse of gene activation. (A) Activator A is induced fast; repressor R is induced slowly by A; both control gene X (AND NOT logic). (B) When KA << KR, a transient pulse of protein X occurs. (C) When KA >> KR, a sustained output is produced.
- *Figure 8–88:* A coherent feed-forward motif filters transient inputs. (A) Both activators A1 and A2 (induced sequentially by the same input) are required to express gene X. (B) Brief input pulses produce little or no output. (C) Only sustained inputs drive strong gene expression—acting as a noise filter.
- *Figure 8–89:* Stochastic gene expression in individual E. coli cells. Two reporter genes (green and red fluorescence) are driven by the same promoter in all bacteria; nevertheless, cells show variable fluorescence levels, demonstrating that gene expression is noisy and that identical cells can differ substantially in protein content.
